{"parentUuid":"b06a27eb-4823-4a83-976e-82fdf70d7752","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Xd6uKbDpCYz2K5ixtCHB5i","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01EpsTotcRD8GXrGnbfwQ91j","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync/README.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":295,"cache_read_input_tokens":42466,"output_tokens":88,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":295,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011Ca5CECuHyrZ24vRBrQREw","type":"assistant","uuid":"d740e6b4-12f1-4f92-be2c-c2df85cab65c","timestamp":"2026-04-15T07:52:45.671Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","sessionId":"c7d001b2-f56b-4999-82ed-3af83b6837b6","version":"2.1.91","gitBranch":"soph/plan-optimization","slug":"jazzy-sprouting-riddle"}
{"parentUuid":"d740e6b4-12f1-4f92-be2c-c2df85cab65c","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"15e5e9dd-55d1-4298-ab50-6c1b40407061","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EpsTotcRD8GXrGnbfwQ91j","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# git-sync\n2\t\n3\t`git-sync` mirrors refs from a source remote to a target remote without creating a local checkout. It uses an in-memory `go-git` object store and talks smart HTTP directly:\n4\t\n5\t- `info/refs` ref advertisement for source and target\n6\t- `upload-pack` fetch from source with target tip hashes advertised as `have`\n7\t- `receive-pack` push to target with explicit ref update commands and a streamed packfile\n8\t\n9\tThat keeps the target side incremental without fetching target objects into the local process first.\n10\t\n11\t## Why This Exists\n12\t\n13\tGit already has pieces of this problem, but not this exact tool shape.\n14\t\n15\tWhat usually exists today:\n16\t\n17\t- a full local `git clone --mirror` followed by `git push --mirror`\n18\t- host-specific import or migration features\n19\t- CI jobs or shell scripts that glue fetch and push steps together\n20\t- one-off migration tooling tied to a specific platform\n21\t\n22\tWhat those approaches usually do not give you:\n23\t\n24\t- direct remote-to-remote relay behavior\n25\t- a small standalone CLI with explicit sync semantics\n26\t- front-loaded validation and planning\n27\t- machine-readable output for automation\n28\t- one tool that covers empty-target bootstrap, normal sync, and large-repo bootstrap fallback\n29\t\n30\tThat is the gap `git-sync` is trying to fill.\n31\t\n32\tThe main value is operational:\n33\t\n34\t- avoid requiring a full local mirror checkout just to move refs between remotes\n35\t- make initial seeding of large repositories cheaper and more predictable\n36\t- keep incremental sync behavior explicit and safe\n37\t- give operators and automation a stable way to inspect, plan, execute, and benchmark the same workflows\n38\t\n39\tThis is especially useful when:\n40\t\n41\t- the target is a new hosted Git service or internal Git endpoint\n42\t- bootstrap size matters more than local developer ergonomics\n43\t- you want a repeatable machine-oriented sync primitive rather than an ad hoc migration script\n44\t- you need clearer control over mapping, pruning, force rules, and relay behavior than generic shell glue usually provides\n45\t\n46\tCompared to a service that keeps persistent local clones, `git-sync` is the better fit when:\n47\t\n48\t- relay is common enough that streaming source-to-target is the normal case\n49\t- avoiding persistent local repo storage is an operational advantage\n50\t- remote-to-remote efficiency matters more than full local Git generality\n51\t\n52\tIf you need arbitrary complex reconciliation through one always-warm local full-state model, a local-clone service is still the more general tool.\n53\t\n54\tThe command surface is:\n55\t\n56\t- `git-sync probe`: inspect a source remote, and optionally a target remote\n57\t- `git-sync fetch`: exercise source-side fetch negotiation without pushing\n58\t- `git-sync bootstrap`: seed an empty target with create-only relay behavior\n59\t- `git-sync plan`: compute source-to-target ref actions without pushing, with `--mode sync|replicate`\n60\t- `git-sync sync`: execute the planned changes against the target\n61\t- `git-sync replicate`: execute source-authoritative relay-only replication against the target\n62\t- `git-sync-bench`: run repeatable benchmark scenarios against fresh empty targets\n63\t\n64\t## Library API\n65\t\n66\t`git-sync` now has a two-tier Go API:\n67\t\n68\t- `pkg/gitsync`\n69\t  - stable embedding surface for queue workers and other external callers\n70\t  - typed `Probe`, `Plan`, `Sync`, and `Replicate` requests/results\n71\t  - injected auth and HTTP client support\n72\t- `pkg/gitsync/unstable`\n73\t  - explicitly non-stable surface for first-party tooling and advanced controls\n74\t  - includes `Bootstrap`, `Fetch`, batching and measurement knobs, and CLI-oriented execution options\n75\t\n76\tIf you are embedding `git-sync` outside this repo, prefer `pkg/gitsync`. The CLI and benchmark command use `pkg/gitsync/unstable` because they still need direct access to advanced engine controls that are intentionally not part of the stable API.\n77\t\n78\tThe stable `pkg/gitsync` results are shaped for workers:\n79\t\n80\t- `Refs`\n81\t  - per-ref outcomes\n82\t- `Counts`\n83\t  - aggregate applied/skipped/blocked/deleted counts\n84\t- `Execution`\n85\t  - execution mode, protocol, relay summary, and batch summary\n86\t\n87\tSee [docs/embedding.md](docs/embedding.md) for worker-oriented guidance.\n88\t\n89\t## Current scope\n90\t\n91\t- Smart HTTP only\n92\t- No local working tree\n93\t- Branch mirroring by default\n94\t- Optional tag mirroring with `--tags`\n95\t- Optional exact ref mapping with `--map`\n96\t- Fast-forward safety by default\n97\t- Optional forced retargeting with `--force`\n98\t- Optional source-authoritative relay-only replication with `replicate` / `plan --mode replicate`\n99\t- Optional managed-ref deletion with `--prune`\n100\t- Optional transfer stats output with `--stats`\n101\t- Optional machine-readable output with `--json`\n102\t- Optional source-side Git protocol v2 for `ls-refs` and `fetch`\n103\t\n104\t## Limits\n105\t\n106\t- Push still uses the existing v1-style `receive-pack` path.\n107\t- Protocol v2 support currently covers source discovery and source fetch only.\n108\t- `--protocol auto` tries source-side v2 first and falls back to v1.\n109\t- `--protocol v2` requires the source remote to negotiate v2.\n110\t- Ref mapping is explicit, not wildcard-based.\n111\t- Only smart HTTP remotes are supported.\n112\t- Objects are kept in memory for the duration of the run.\n113\t- Non-relay materialized syncs are bounded by `--materialized-max-objects`, an object-count guardrail for the in-memory fallback path.\n114\t\n115\t## Quick Start\n116\t\n117\t```bash\n118\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n119\t  --source-token \"$GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN\" \\\n120\t  --target-token \"$GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN\" \\\n121\t  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n122\t  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n123\t```\n124\t\n125\t## Commands\n126\t\n127\tPlan a sync without pushing anything:\n128\t\n129\t```bash\n130\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n131\t  --stats \\\n132\t  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n133\t  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n134\t```\n135\t\n136\tPlan a source-authoritative replication without pushing anything:\n137\t\n138\t```bash\n139\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n140\t  --mode replicate \\\n141\t  --stats \\\n142\t  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n143\t  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n144\t```\n145\t\n146\tExecute relay-only replication that overwrites differing managed refs and fails instead of materializing locally:\n147\t\n148\t```bash\n149\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync replicate \\\n150\t  --stats \\\n151\t  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n152\t  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n153\t```\n154\t\n155\tIf `replicate` cannot use relay against the target, it fails and tells you to rerun with `sync`.\n156\t\n157\tBootstrap an empty target without using the normal local object-store sync path:\n158\t\n159\t```bash\n160\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n161\t  --stats \\\n162\t  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n163\t  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n164\t```\n165\t\n166\tAdd `--max-pack-bytes` to abort bootstrap if the streamed source pack grows past a safety threshold:\n167\t\n168\t```bash\n169\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n170\t  --max-pack-bytes 104857600 \\\n171\t  <source-url> \\\n172\t  <target-url>\n173\t```\n174\t\n175\tAdd `--target-max-pack-bytes` to split large branch bootstraps into multiple relay batches with temporary refs:\n176\t\n177\t```bash\n178\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n179\t  --target-max-pack-bytes 1073741824 \\\n180\t  <source-url> \\\n181\t  <target-url>\n182\t```\n183\t\n184\tCurrent batching scope is intentionally narrow:\n185\t\n186\t- protocol v2 only\n187\t- branch refs are batched\n188\t- optional create-only tags are pushed after branch batches complete\n189\t- temporary refs under `refs/gitsync/bootstrap/heads/`\n190\t- resume from existing temp refs is supported when they match a planned checkpoint\n191\t\n192\tThis mode is intended as an advanced large-repo fallback, not the default bootstrap path. Use plain `bootstrap` first when a single streamed initial sync is acceptable.\n193\t\n194\tA practical starting point is:\n195\t\n196\t- `--target-max-pack-bytes 536870912` for a conservative `512 MiB` target-side batch size\n197\t- `--target-max-pack-bytes 1073741824` when you want fewer, larger batches and the target has more headroom\n198\t\n199\tFor example:\n200\t\n201\t```bash\n202\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n203\t  --target-max-pack-bytes 536870912 \\\n204\t  --protocol v2 \\\n205\t  -v \\\n206\t  <source-url> \\\n207\t  <target-url>\n208\t```\n209\t\n210\tAdd `--measure-memory` to `bootstrap`, `sync`, `plan`, `probe`, or `fetch` to sample elapsed time and Go heap usage:\n211\t\n212\t```bash\n213\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n214\t  --measure-memory \\\n215\t  --json \\\n216\t  <source-url> \\\n217\t  <target-url>\n218\t```\n219\t\n220\tThat is useful for one-off measurements on the same fixture or test repo.\n221\t\n222\t## Benchmarking\n223\t\n224\tFor repeated benchmark runs, prefer the dedicated benchmark command instead of manually wrapping `git-sync` invocations:\n225\t\n226\t```bash\n227\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync-bench \\\n228\t  --scenario bootstrap \\\n229\t  --source-url /tmp/git-sync-bench/kubernetes.git \\\n230\t  --repeat 3 \\\n231\t  --target-max-pack-bytes 104857600 \\\n232\t  --stats \\\n233\t  --json\n234\t```\n235\t\n236\t`git-sync-bench` creates a fresh bare target repository for each run, executes the selected scenario in-process, and reports:\n237\t\n238\t- per-run wall-clock time\n239\t- per-run `syncer.Result`\n240\t- aggregate min/avg/max wall time\n241\t- aggregate internal elapsed and heap metrics from `--measure-memory`\n242\t- relay modes observed across successful runs\n243\t\n244\tIf `--source-url` is a local path, it is converted to `file://...` automatically. The current scenarios are:\n245\t\n246\t- `--scenario bootstrap`\n247\t- `--scenario sync`\n248\t\n249\tFor large-repo measurements, use a local bare mirror as the source so the benchmark reflects `git-sync` behavior rather than internet variance. See [docs/benchmarking.md](docs/benchmarking.md) for details.\n250\t\n251\t## Sync Behavior\n252\t\n253\tWhen `sync` sees that all managed target refs are absent and the run is compatible with bootstrap semantics, it automatically uses the bootstrap relay path instead of the normal decode-and-repack sync path.\n254\t\n255\t`sync` also uses a narrow incremental relay path for fast-forward branch updates and tag creation when there is no prune/delete, no force, and the target does not advertise `no-thin`. This now includes multi-branch batches, branch-to-branch mappings, and create-only tags. Tag retargeting and other more complex updates still fall back to the normal local decode-and-repack path.\n256\t\n257\tIf `sync` falls back to the materialized path, `--materialized-max-objects` sets an explicit object-count safety bound for the in-memory object set. It is a conservative guardrail, not a precise heap-size limit.\n258\t\n259\tSync specific branches:\n260\t\n261\t```bash\n262\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n263\t  --branch main,release \\\n264\t  --source-token \"$GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN\" \\\n265\t  --target-token \"$GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN\" \\\n266\t  <source-url> \\\n267\t  <target-url>\n268\t```\n269\t\n270\tMap a source branch to a different target branch:\n271\t\n272\t```bash\n273\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n274\t  --map main:stable \\\n275\t  <source-url> \\\n276\t  <target-url>\n277\t```\n278\t\n279\tMirror tags and prune managed target refs that disappeared from source:\n280\t\n281\t```bash\n282\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n283\t  --tags \\\n284\t  --prune \\\n285\t  <source-url> \\\n286\t  <target-url>\n287\t```\n288\t\n289\tForce source-side protocol v2:\n290\t\n291\t```bash\n292\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n293\t  --protocol v2 \\\n294\t  <source-url> \\\n295\t  <target-url>\n296\t```\n297\t\n298\tProbe a source remote without pushing anything:\n299\t\n300\t```bash\n301\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync probe \\\n302\t  --stats \\\n303\t  --tags \\\n304\t  --protocol auto \\\n305\t  <source-url>\n306\t```\n307\t\n308\tProbe both source and target remotes to inspect source fetch capabilities and target `receive-pack` capabilities:\n309\t\n310\t```bash\n311\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync probe \\\n312\t  --stats \\\n313\t  <source-url> \\\n314\t  <target-url>\n315\t```\n316\t\n317\tFetch from a source remote into memory without pushing anywhere:\n318\t\n319\t```bash\n320\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync fetch \\\n321\t  --stats \\\n322\t  --protocol auto \\\n323\t  --branch main \\\n324\t  <source-url>\n325\t```\n326\t\n327\tAdvertise an existing source ref as a synthetic `have` to exercise incremental negotiation:\n328\t\n329\t```bash\n330\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync fetch \\\n331\t  --stats \\\n332\t  --protocol auto \\\n333\t  --branch main \\\n334\t  --have-ref main \\\n335\t  <source-url>\n336\t```\n337\t\n338\tDry run:\n339\t\n340\t```bash\n341\tgo run ./cmd/git-sync plan --stats <source-url> <target-url>\n342\t```\n343\t\n344\t## JSON Output\n345\t\n346\tAdd `--json` to `probe`, `fetch`, `bootstrap`, `plan`, or `sync` to emit machine-readable output instead of the default text format.\n347\t\n348\tThe JSON interface is intentionally stable:\n349\t\n350\t- keys use `snake_case`\n351\t- refs and hashes are serialized as strings, not raw byte arrays\n352\t- `probe` returns top-level keys such as `source_url`, `target_url`, `protocol`, `ref_prefixes`, `source_capabilities`, `target_capabilities`, `refs`, and `stats`\n353\t- `fetch` returns top-level keys such as `source_url`, `protocol`, `wants`, `haves`, `fetched_objects`, and `stats`\n354\t- `bootstrap`, `plan`, and `sync` return top-level keys such as `plans`, `pushed`, `skipped`, `blocked`, `deleted`, `dry_run`, `protocol`, and `stats`\n355\t- `bootstrap`, `plan`, and `sync` also expose `relay`, `relay_mode`, `relay_reason`, `batching`, `batch_count`, `planned_batch_count`, and `temp_refs`\n356\t- each item in `plans` includes stable string fields such as `branch`, `source_ref`, `target_ref`, `source_hash`, `target_hash`, `kind`, `action`, and `reason`\n357\t\n358\t## Auth\n359\t\n360\tFor GitHub and similar providers, use basic auth with a token as the password.\n361\t\n362\tAuth is resolved in this order:\n363\t\n364\t- explicit CLI flags\n365\t- `GITSYNC_*` environment variables\n366\t- local `git credential fill` helper lookup for `http` and `https` remotes\n367\t- anonymous access\n368\t\n369\tRelevant variables:\n370\t\n371\t- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN`\n372\t- `GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN`\n373\t- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_USERNAME` default: `git`\n374\t- `GITSYNC_TARGET_USERNAME` default: `git`\n375\t\n376\tBearer auth is also available:\n377\t\n378\t- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_BEARER_TOKEN`\n379\t- `GITSYNC_TARGET_BEARER_TOKEN`\n380\t\n381\tThat means local testing against a dummy GitHub repo can reuse your regular Git credential helper setup without passing tokens on every command.\n382\t\n383\t## Protocol Notes\n384\t\n385\t- Source refs are listed with `GET /info/refs?service=git-upload-pack`.\n386\t- When the source supports it, the client can negotiate protocol v2 with `Git-Protocol: version=2`, then use `ls-refs` and `fetch`.\n387\t- Target refs are listed with `GET /info/refs?service=git-receive-pack`.\n388\t- The source fetch advertises current target tip hashes as `have`, so reruns download less when source and target already share history.\n389\t- Target push stays on the current `receive-pack` path.\n390\t- If a target ref does not exist, it is created.\n391\t- If a target ref already matches the source, it is skipped.\n392\t- Branches are updated only when the target tip is an ancestor of the source tip, unless `--force` is set.\n393\t- Tags are immutable by default. Retargeting an existing tag requires `--force`.\n394\t- If `--prune` is set, managed target refs that are absent on source are deleted.\n395\t- `plan` never pushes. If `sync` finds blocked refs, it exits non-zero before pushing anything.\n396\t- `--stats` adds per-service request, byte, want, have, and command counters to the output.\n397\t\n398\tPush still uses the current low-level `receive-pack` path. Protocol v2 is used where it materially improves this tool: source-side ref discovery and source-side object download.\n399\t\n400\t## Testing\n401\t\n402\tDefault suite:\n403\t\n404\t```bash\n405\tenv GOCACHE=/tmp/go-build go test ./...\n406\t```\n407\t\n408\tExtended and environment-specific test instructions are in [docs/testing.md](docs/testing.md).\n409\t\n410\t## Design Notes\n411\t\n412\t`bootstrap` is the dedicated path for large initial syncs into an empty target. The goal is to relay a fetched source pack directly into target `receive-pack` instead of decoding the full object graph into local memory first.\n413\t\n414\tCurrent architectural summary and package boundaries are in [docs/architecture.md](docs/architecture.md).\n415\t\n416\tThe design note is in [docs/bootstrap.md](docs/bootstrap.md).\n417\t\n418\tFor very large single-branch repositories, there is also a batching design and initial implementation note in [docs/bootstrap-batching.md](docs/bootstrap-batching.md).\n419\t"}]},"uuid":"d954ac07-3387-41b1-84dc-8a3efe09c3a8","timestamp":"2026-04-15T07:52:46.081Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync/README.md","content":"# git-sync\n\n`git-sync` mirrors refs from a source remote to a target remote without creating a local checkout. It uses an in-memory `go-git` object store and talks smart HTTP directly:\n\n- `info/refs` ref advertisement for source and target\n- `upload-pack` fetch from source with target tip hashes advertised as `have`\n- `receive-pack` push to target with explicit ref update commands and a streamed packfile\n\nThat keeps the target side incremental without fetching target objects into the local process first.\n\n## Why This Exists\n\nGit already has pieces of this problem, but not this exact tool shape.\n\nWhat usually exists today:\n\n- a full local `git clone --mirror` followed by `git push --mirror`\n- host-specific import or migration features\n- CI jobs or shell scripts that glue fetch and push steps together\n- one-off migration tooling tied to a specific platform\n\nWhat those approaches usually do not give you:\n\n- direct remote-to-remote relay behavior\n- a small standalone CLI with explicit sync semantics\n- front-loaded validation and planning\n- machine-readable output for automation\n- one tool that covers empty-target bootstrap, normal sync, and large-repo bootstrap fallback\n\nThat is the gap `git-sync` is trying to fill.\n\nThe main value is operational:\n\n- avoid requiring a full local mirror checkout just to move refs between remotes\n- make initial seeding of large repositories cheaper and more predictable\n- keep incremental sync behavior explicit and safe\n- give operators and automation a stable way to inspect, plan, execute, and benchmark the same workflows\n\nThis is especially useful when:\n\n- the target is a new hosted Git service or internal Git endpoint\n- bootstrap size matters more than local developer ergonomics\n- you want a repeatable machine-oriented sync primitive rather than an ad hoc migration script\n- you need clearer control over mapping, pruning, force rules, and relay behavior than generic shell glue usually provides\n\nCompared to a service that keeps persistent local clones, `git-sync` is the better fit when:\n\n- relay is common enough that streaming source-to-target is the normal case\n- avoiding persistent local repo storage is an operational advantage\n- remote-to-remote efficiency matters more than full local Git generality\n\nIf you need arbitrary complex reconciliation through one always-warm local full-state model, a local-clone service is still the more general tool.\n\nThe command surface is:\n\n- `git-sync probe`: inspect a source remote, and optionally a target remote\n- `git-sync fetch`: exercise source-side fetch negotiation without pushing\n- `git-sync bootstrap`: seed an empty target with create-only relay behavior\n- `git-sync plan`: compute source-to-target ref actions without pushing, with `--mode sync|replicate`\n- `git-sync sync`: execute the planned changes against the target\n- `git-sync replicate`: execute source-authoritative relay-only replication against the target\n- `git-sync-bench`: run repeatable benchmark scenarios against fresh empty targets\n\n## Library API\n\n`git-sync` now has a two-tier Go API:\n\n- `pkg/gitsync`\n  - stable embedding surface for queue workers and other external callers\n  - typed `Probe`, `Plan`, `Sync`, and `Replicate` requests/results\n  - injected auth and HTTP client support\n- `pkg/gitsync/unstable`\n  - explicitly non-stable surface for first-party tooling and advanced controls\n  - includes `Bootstrap`, `Fetch`, batching and measurement knobs, and CLI-oriented execution options\n\nIf you are embedding `git-sync` outside this repo, prefer `pkg/gitsync`. The CLI and benchmark command use `pkg/gitsync/unstable` because they still need direct access to advanced engine controls that are intentionally not part of the stable API.\n\nThe stable `pkg/gitsync` results are shaped for workers:\n\n- `Refs`\n  - per-ref outcomes\n- `Counts`\n  - aggregate applied/skipped/blocked/deleted counts\n- `Execution`\n  - execution mode, protocol, relay summary, and batch summary\n\nSee [docs/embedding.md](docs/embedding.md) for worker-oriented guidance.\n\n## Current scope\n\n- Smart HTTP only\n- No local working tree\n- Branch mirroring by default\n- Optional tag mirroring with `--tags`\n- Optional exact ref mapping with `--map`\n- Fast-forward safety by default\n- Optional forced retargeting with `--force`\n- Optional source-authoritative relay-only replication with `replicate` / `plan --mode replicate`\n- Optional managed-ref deletion with `--prune`\n- Optional transfer stats output with `--stats`\n- Optional machine-readable output with `--json`\n- Optional source-side Git protocol v2 for `ls-refs` and `fetch`\n\n## Limits\n\n- Push still uses the existing v1-style `receive-pack` path.\n- Protocol v2 support currently covers source discovery and source fetch only.\n- `--protocol auto` tries source-side v2 first and falls back to v1.\n- `--protocol v2` requires the source remote to negotiate v2.\n- Ref mapping is explicit, not wildcard-based.\n- Only smart HTTP remotes are supported.\n- Objects are kept in memory for the duration of the run.\n- Non-relay materialized syncs are bounded by `--materialized-max-objects`, an object-count guardrail for the in-memory fallback path.\n\n## Quick Start\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --source-token \"$GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN\" \\\n  --target-token \"$GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN\" \\\n  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n```\n\n## Commands\n\nPlan a sync without pushing anything:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n  --stats \\\n  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n```\n\nPlan a source-authoritative replication without pushing anything:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync plan \\\n  --mode replicate \\\n  --stats \\\n  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n```\n\nExecute relay-only replication that overwrites differing managed refs and fails instead of materializing locally:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync replicate \\\n  --stats \\\n  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n```\n\nIf `replicate` cannot use relay against the target, it fails and tells you to rerun with `sync`.\n\nBootstrap an empty target without using the normal local object-store sync path:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n  --stats \\\n  https://github.com/source-org/source-repo.git \\\n  https://github.com/target-org/target-repo.git\n```\n\nAdd `--max-pack-bytes` to abort bootstrap if the streamed source pack grows past a safety threshold:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n  --max-pack-bytes 104857600 \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nAdd `--target-max-pack-bytes` to split large branch bootstraps into multiple relay batches with temporary refs:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n  --target-max-pack-bytes 1073741824 \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nCurrent batching scope is intentionally narrow:\n\n- protocol v2 only\n- branch refs are batched\n- optional create-only tags are pushed after branch batches complete\n- temporary refs under `refs/gitsync/bootstrap/heads/`\n- resume from existing temp refs is supported when they match a planned checkpoint\n\nThis mode is intended as an advanced large-repo fallback, not the default bootstrap path. Use plain `bootstrap` first when a single streamed initial sync is acceptable.\n\nA practical starting point is:\n\n- `--target-max-pack-bytes 536870912` for a conservative `512 MiB` target-side batch size\n- `--target-max-pack-bytes 1073741824` when you want fewer, larger batches and the target has more headroom\n\nFor example:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n  --target-max-pack-bytes 536870912 \\\n  --protocol v2 \\\n  -v \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nAdd `--measure-memory` to `bootstrap`, `sync`, `plan`, `probe`, or `fetch` to sample elapsed time and Go heap usage:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync bootstrap \\\n  --measure-memory \\\n  --json \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nThat is useful for one-off measurements on the same fixture or test repo.\n\n## Benchmarking\n\nFor repeated benchmark runs, prefer the dedicated benchmark command instead of manually wrapping `git-sync` invocations:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync-bench \\\n  --scenario bootstrap \\\n  --source-url /tmp/git-sync-bench/kubernetes.git \\\n  --repeat 3 \\\n  --target-max-pack-bytes 104857600 \\\n  --stats \\\n  --json\n```\n\n`git-sync-bench` creates a fresh bare target repository for each run, executes the selected scenario in-process, and reports:\n\n- per-run wall-clock time\n- per-run `syncer.Result`\n- aggregate min/avg/max wall time\n- aggregate internal elapsed and heap metrics from `--measure-memory`\n- relay modes observed across successful runs\n\nIf `--source-url` is a local path, it is converted to `file://...` automatically. The current scenarios are:\n\n- `--scenario bootstrap`\n- `--scenario sync`\n\nFor large-repo measurements, use a local bare mirror as the source so the benchmark reflects `git-sync` behavior rather than internet variance. See [docs/benchmarking.md](docs/benchmarking.md) for details.\n\n## Sync Behavior\n\nWhen `sync` sees that all managed target refs are absent and the run is compatible with bootstrap semantics, it automatically uses the bootstrap relay path instead of the normal decode-and-repack sync path.\n\n`sync` also uses a narrow incremental relay path for fast-forward branch updates and tag creation when there is no prune/delete, no force, and the target does not advertise `no-thin`. This now includes multi-branch batches, branch-to-branch mappings, and create-only tags. Tag retargeting and other more complex updates still fall back to the normal local decode-and-repack path.\n\nIf `sync` falls back to the materialized path, `--materialized-max-objects` sets an explicit object-count safety bound for the in-memory object set. It is a conservative guardrail, not a precise heap-size limit.\n\nSync specific branches:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --branch main,release \\\n  --source-token \"$GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN\" \\\n  --target-token \"$GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN\" \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nMap a source branch to a different target branch:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --map main:stable \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nMirror tags and prune managed target refs that disappeared from source:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --tags \\\n  --prune \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nForce source-side protocol v2:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync sync \\\n  --protocol v2 \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nProbe a source remote without pushing anything:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync probe \\\n  --stats \\\n  --tags \\\n  --protocol auto \\\n  <source-url>\n```\n\nProbe both source and target remotes to inspect source fetch capabilities and target `receive-pack` capabilities:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync probe \\\n  --stats \\\n  <source-url> \\\n  <target-url>\n```\n\nFetch from a source remote into memory without pushing anywhere:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync fetch \\\n  --stats \\\n  --protocol auto \\\n  --branch main \\\n  <source-url>\n```\n\nAdvertise an existing source ref as a synthetic `have` to exercise incremental negotiation:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync fetch \\\n  --stats \\\n  --protocol auto \\\n  --branch main \\\n  --have-ref main \\\n  <source-url>\n```\n\nDry run:\n\n```bash\ngo run ./cmd/git-sync plan --stats <source-url> <target-url>\n```\n\n## JSON Output\n\nAdd `--json` to `probe`, `fetch`, `bootstrap`, `plan`, or `sync` to emit machine-readable output instead of the default text format.\n\nThe JSON interface is intentionally stable:\n\n- keys use `snake_case`\n- refs and hashes are serialized as strings, not raw byte arrays\n- `probe` returns top-level keys such as `source_url`, `target_url`, `protocol`, `ref_prefixes`, `source_capabilities`, `target_capabilities`, `refs`, and `stats`\n- `fetch` returns top-level keys such as `source_url`, `protocol`, `wants`, `haves`, `fetched_objects`, and `stats`\n- `bootstrap`, `plan`, and `sync` return top-level keys such as `plans`, `pushed`, `skipped`, `blocked`, `deleted`, `dry_run`, `protocol`, and `stats`\n- `bootstrap`, `plan`, and `sync` also expose `relay`, `relay_mode`, `relay_reason`, `batching`, `batch_count`, `planned_batch_count`, and `temp_refs`\n- each item in `plans` includes stable string fields such as `branch`, `source_ref`, `target_ref`, `source_hash`, `target_hash`, `kind`, `action`, and `reason`\n\n## Auth\n\nFor GitHub and similar providers, use basic auth with a token as the password.\n\nAuth is resolved in this order:\n\n- explicit CLI flags\n- `GITSYNC_*` environment variables\n- local `git credential fill` helper lookup for `http` and `https` remotes\n- anonymous access\n\nRelevant variables:\n\n- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_TOKEN`\n- `GITSYNC_TARGET_TOKEN`\n- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_USERNAME` default: `git`\n- `GITSYNC_TARGET_USERNAME` default: `git`\n\nBearer auth is also available:\n\n- `GITSYNC_SOURCE_BEARER_TOKEN`\n- `GITSYNC_TARGET_BEARER_TOKEN`\n\nThat means local testing against a dummy GitHub repo can reuse your regular Git credential helper setup without passing tokens on every command.\n\n## Protocol Notes\n\n- Source refs are listed with `GET /info/refs?service=git-upload-pack`.\n- When the source supports it, the client can negotiate protocol v2 with `Git-Protocol: version=2`, then use `ls-refs` and `fetch`.\n- Target refs are listed with `GET /info/refs?service=git-receive-pack`.\n- The source fetch advertises current target tip hashes as `have`, so reruns download less when source and target already share history.\n- Target push stays on the current `receive-pack` path.\n- If a target ref does not exist, it is created.\n- If a target ref already matches the source, it is skipped.\n- Branches are updated only when the target tip is an ancestor of the source tip, unless `--force` is set.\n- Tags are immutable by default. Retargeting an existing tag requires `--force`.\n- If `--prune` is set, managed target refs that are absent on source are deleted.\n- `plan` never pushes. If `sync` finds blocked refs, it exits non-zero before pushing anything.\n- `--stats` adds per-service request, byte, want, have, and command counters to the output.\n\nPush still uses the current low-level `receive-pack` path. Protocol v2 is used where it materially improves this tool: source-side ref discovery and source-side object download.\n\n## Testing\n\nDefault suite:\n\n```bash\nenv GOCACHE=/tmp/go-build go test ./...\n```\n\nExtended and environment-specific test instructions are in [docs/testing.md](docs/testing.md).\n\n## Design Notes\n\n`bootstrap` is the dedicated path for large initial syncs into an empty target. The goal is to relay a fetched source pack directly into target `receive-pack` instead of decoding the full object graph into local memory first.\n\nCurrent architectural summary and package boundaries are in [docs/architecture.md](docs/architecture.md).\n\nThe design note is in [docs/bootstrap.md](docs/bootstrap.md).\n\nFor very large single-branch repositories, there is also a batching design and initial implementation note in [docs/bootstrap-batching.md](docs/bootstrap-batching.md).\n","numLines":419,"startLine":1,"totalLines":419}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d740e6b4-12f1-4f92-be2c-c2df85cab65c","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync","sessionId":"c7d001b2-f56b-4999-82ed-3af83b6837b6","version":"2.1.91","gitBranch":"soph/plan-optimization","slug":"jazzy-sprouting-riddle"}
